>>>diy/general9 1919 cscott(1322)13mar10 14:16 c1899*m

If you are buying a uPVC or composite door, check the construction very 
carefully.  A uPVC door with a one-piece moulded panel *will* crack and 
leak, as will a composite door of similar construction.  Ideally a uPVC 
door should be constructed like a window, with panels and/or sealed units 
fitting into a frame.  The moulded panels have several problems, quite 
aside from looking cheap!  First, they are sealed to any window with an 
adhesive, and the seal very often breaks down.  Second, the stresses left 
in the material from the moulding process inevitably come back to haunt 
them, and if you look any reasonable sample of such doors you will find 
cracks and splits radiating from the corners of the letter-box and the 
corners of the window.  Composite doors are OK if the panel is in GRP 
(fibreglass to old-timers like me!), which is laid down in the mould 
rather than being heat- and stress-moulded, and if the design avoids the 
need to glue the panel to the glass ...

A *good* hardwood door would be an excellent choice, though it is likely 
to cost several times as much as any other type of door.

Again, remember you get what you pay for, and buying on price rather than 
quality is always going to cost you more in the long run.

I could offer other advice, but I'll restrain myself.  :-)

Colin


