HDRs are a type of photography. It stands for High Dynamic Range.

If you take a photograph inside a room pointing out a window then if you 
expose it for the daylight outside then the room is dark but if you expose 
for the room the daylight is bright white. HDR can expose the shot so that 
you have the outside and inside visible.

There are plenty of examples on the web but I tend to use the method for 
mostly church photography, inside and out.

There are also a variety of ways to both take and expose the photographs. 
One of the methods I use is to shoot in raw format and then use the raw 
software to expose 3 stops over then 3 stops under as well as the taken 
photograph and merge them together. Some do end up with a good effect.

http://www.flickr.com/photos/covltwt/2270350914/

However, the main option I do involves taking between 3 and 7 shots at 
differing levels of exposure on the tripod. Some results are better than 
others.

http://www.flickr.com/photos/covltwt/1095449170/
http://www.flickr.com/photos/covltwt/2879698425/

They both use the same method but are quite different. I get carried away 
with what I think the amount of colour should be and sometimes it goes 
pear shaped. However, the former of those two images were enough to 
astound the members of the church that saw them and I believe have been 
used now by the church for their use. I was careful with the copyright for 
them as well as their attitude of 'just give us the masters and we'll sort 
it out'

http://www.flickr.com/photos/covltwt/3299059390/ I have a non-cloud 
version that when shown together give people the impression I faked this 
picture. However, considering they were taken several hours apart and I 
had been inside taking photos usually calms them down. FYI I didn't and I 
don't think I know how to yet.

http://www.flickr.com/photos/covltwt/3299063568/ This one shows the point 
above which I made. If I had exposed for outside you wouldn't have seen 
the detail of the doorway.

Some photos are better than others. Some have been taken in a hurry or 
just didn't come out as expected.

