I think most people automatically took Mac's side, and Neil went out of 
his way to consider Saga's side. And this is necessary and useful, in a 
dispute: to consider how things look from the other side, and how, when a 
mistake is made and damage done, it's not necessarily fair if it's the 
other side who have to pay for all of it. His assumptions here aren't 
wild, they are just different to other people's.

I also don't think he decided these were "the facts". His language is 
couched in probabilities. He doesn't say what she says is untrue, he says 
he finds it hard to believe. He gives reasoned justification for every 
step he takes. He's aware of the uncertainties.

There is probably an element of post-hoc rationalisation, and I do think 
that's universal. Humans are good at it; we're genetically engineered to 
speculate about mechanisms and possibilities. (Indeed, it's what we're 
doing when we try to imagine Neil's state of mind; we're doing to him 
roughly what he did with Mac, and probably about as erroneously).

And there's something called "confirmation bias", where-by we seek to 
confirm our theories instead of seeking to disprove them. Facts are rarely 
unambiguous and can usually be interpreted to fit, so they don't provide 
much of a reality-check.


