The informed view, ever since Windows 7 came out, is that Windows 7 
thrashes Vista performancewise and in elegance of use.  Which indeed it 
does bigtime.

However, the more informed view is that you should first consider why you 
want to upgrade -- if everything (both with the Vista machine and the XP 
one) is working fine for you, there is a strong argument for leaving them 
alone.  Computers are just tools, after all, and if they are working...

As a decision point, anything with less than 2 Gb of RAM almost certainly 
isn't going to be man enough.  Also, consider your devices such as video 
card, printer, etc, and your important applications -- check that there 
are Windows 7 drivers for your hardware and that the software applications 
are compatible.  Windows 7 is pretty amazing for hardware recognition and 
support, but you need to check whether your exact models will be covered.  

Printers in particular can be an unwanted surprise, sometimes even if 
there is a Windows 7 driver, sometimes they've turned out to have a lot of 
the features missing from the new driver. 

64 bit is also something to consider.  It'll make more efficient use of 
memory above 3 Gb, but there can be hardware driver issues.

A good tip is to do a Google search for, say, your printer model, using a 
search string such, for example, as "HP Laserjet 4 Windows 7 problems" -- 
if there are issues, chances are somebody will already have encountered 
them.




